Background

In a Stroop task, participants are presented with a list of words, with each word displayed in a color of ink. The participants task is to say out loud the color of the ink in which the word is printed. The task has two conditions: a congruent words condition, and an incongruent words condition. In the congruent words condition, the words being displayed are color words whose names match the colors in which they are printed: for example RED, BLUE. In the incongruent words condition, the words displayed are color words whose names do not match the colors in which they are printed: for example PURPLE, ORANGE. In each case, we measure the time it takes to name the ink colors in equally-sized lists. Each participant will go through and record a time from each condition.

Dependent-Samples t-tests

We can formulate hypothesis that there is a difference between the time used to recognise colours under congruent words condition and incongruent words condition, namely, the Stroop Effect is in existence. Specifically, here we referring to the population means of congruence words condition and incongruence words condition - average times for the respective condition to recognise the colours. By comparing these means directly, well be able to tell whether there is a difference between the the two conditions colour recognition times.

\[H_0 : \mu_2 - \mu_1= 0\]

\[H_1 : \mu_2 - \mu_1 \neq 0\]

Null Hypothesis \(H_0 : \mu_2 - \mu_1= 0\) :: The group population mean of the differences (\(\mu_2 - \mu_1= 0\)) equals the zero.

Alternative Hypothesis \(H_1 : \mu_2 - \mu_1 \neq 0\):: The group population mean of the difference (\(\mu_2 - \mu_1 \neq 0\)) does not equal to zero.

Statistical test

In this study researcher compares two samples that are dependent. They are dependent because the same subject are assigned to two conditions in random order. Thus, this is within subject design. When we have these within subject designs, we have parired data. So column of xis would corresponds to the variable measurement of one condition. And then the yi values would corresponds to a second treatment. And then, what we want to do is look at the difference between these values, Well call this D sub i. And thats just the x values minus the y values. Or it could be be the opposite. We are really just concerned with absolute difference. Now we follow the same procedure as we did before with one sample t-test, except we used values of D.

However, it wouldnt be possible to do the experiment with all potential subjects in the world, so we need to work with the sample we have on hand to make inference about the population means, i.e., to use the observation means, sd and other statistics to infer about the population means. In this case, the observation is the difference between the two conditions times. With this new data, we can construct new statistics such as means and standard errors.

To achieve this, We can use a two-sided paired student t-test to verify. This is because: one, we need to address the uncertainty in sample standard error resulted from the unknown population standard deviation; two, we are comparing the means of two groups that are dependent; three, the same subject is involved under both conditions.

We know the formula for the one-sample t-test:

\[ t=\frac{\bar{X} - \mu_{\bar(X)}}{s_{\bar{X}}}\]

Difference scores are symbolised with D instead of X. So if you were to conduct a one-sample t-test with difference scores, the formula would be:

\[ t=\frac{\bar{D}-\mu_{\bar{D}}}{s_{\bar{D}}} \] Therefore the mean spelling ability before (\(\mu_1\)) is the same as the mean spelling ability after the program(\(\mu_2\)). Thus if \(\mu_1\) = \(\mu_2\),then \(\mu_1\) - \(\mu_1\) = 0. Why? Because any number minus itself is 0 (e.g., 202 - 202 = 0). Even though we have no idea what the \(\mu_1\) and \(\mu_2\) are, the null hypothesis implies that the difference between them (\(\mu_D\)) is zero.The null hypothesis always says that the mean difference in the population is \(\mu_D\) = 0. Knowing that the population mean of the difference scores is 0, we can simplify the paired-samples t-test formula to:

\[t=\frac{\bar{D}}{s_{\bar{D}}}\]

This means that the observed t is equal to the sample mean of the difference scores divided by the estimated standard error of the difference scores. What is special about this formula is that it contains no population parameters, only sample statistics. It is for this reason that paired-samples t-tests are widely used: There is no need to know any population parameters in advance.

\[ t= \frac{\mu_D - 0}{S/\sqrt{n}}\]

Dot Plot with PointRange Showing Means and 95% CI: Plotting points summarising the data to plot the means of the two condition with an estimate of 95% confidence interval representing the precision of an estimate. A 95% confidence interval means that 95% of the time, the population mean will be within that interval and 5% of the time, the population mean will be outside of that interval. This means you can be 95% confident that the population mean is within your confidence interval. 

# H0:21 = 0
# H1:21  0

# the null value
mu_diff <- 0 
# add a new diff column
dat.diff <- mutate(stroop_data, diff = Congruent - Incongruent)
# grab all the diff values into a vector
diff <- dat.diff$diff 
# sample sd
sigma <- sd(diff) 
# sample mean
diff_bar <- mean(diff) 
# sample size
n <- length(diff)
# degree of freedom
DF <- n - 1 
# standard error
SE <- sigma/sqrt(n) 
# Calculate the T-statistic:
T <- (diff_bar- mu_diff)/SE; T
## [1] -8.020707
# Calculate the p-value
p_value <- pt(T, df = DF, lower.tail = TRUE) * 2; p_value
## [1] 4.103001e-08
# Build the confidence interval based on 5% confidence level
diff_bar + c(1, -1) * qt(.975, df = DF, lower.tail = FALSE) * SE
## [1] -10.019028  -5.910555

Running the Dependent Samples t-test

ttest <- t.test(ResponseTime ~ Condition, data = stroop_data_long, 
                                paired = TRUE, mu = 0, conf.level = 0.95)

tvalue <- ttest$statistic %>% 
          formatC(digit = 2, format = "f")


pvalue <- ttest$p.value %>%
          formatC(digit = 2, format = "f")

df <- ttest$parameter

Results

As can be seen in Table 1 and Figure 1, 2, 3, 4, the mean of Incourgent words condition is significantly higher than the mean of Courgent words condition, \(t(23) = -8.02, p < 0.00\). Thus, we reject null hypothesis that difference in means is equal to 0. One can say thatt naming the colours of colour words (e.g.the words green, red, blue, etc.) is easier and quicker if the actual observed colours of the words match the colors that the words denote (e.g.the colors green, red, blue, etc., respectively) than if they do not match. More precisely, we can say there is a significant difference in the mean task completion times between the two conditions.
